WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.750
...

00:00:01.750 --> 00:00:06.040
in a moment, but it's about a project called Sky

00:00:06.040 --> 00:00:06.380
Limit.

00:00:06.380 --> 00:00:09.040
I started in December, and you can try it live,

00:00:09.120 --> 00:00:10.670
if you like, at skylimit.

00:00:10.940 --> 00:00:12.320
dev, and there's my handle.

00:00:12.320 --> 00:00:16.580
There's an article that appeared in New York Times just like

00:00:16.890 --> 00:00:19.620
three days ago, "The Terrible Cost of Infinite Scroll

00:00:19.620 --> 00:00:23.180
." It was in response to the meta and YouTube judgment,

00:00:23.180 --> 00:00:25.660
and I'm a scientist, and I don't like the

00:00:25.660 --> 00:00:28.420
infinite scroll, and I interact with people who are not very

00:00:28.450 --> 00:00:31.080
popular by likes, but I don't see their posts,

00:00:31.080 --> 00:00:31.600
okay?

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:37.160
So I have a subtype post that describes it.

00:00:37.160 --> 00:00:39.260
The subtitle there is, "What if your social media

00:00:39.260 --> 00:00:41.940
feed work like a newspaper instead of a slot machine, where

00:00:41.940 --> 00:00:44.700
occasionally you get good posts, but you don't know when

00:00:44.820 --> 00:00:45.900
you're going to get it?

00:00:45.900 --> 00:00:48.030
A newspaper, I like the newspaper, I'm an old

00:00:48.030 --> 00:00:51.160
-fashioned guy, I like sections, I read comics,

00:00:51.160 --> 00:00:54.240
and can I reproduce that in Blue Sky?" And actually,

00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:56.960
you can, so that's the point of the talk.

00:00:56.960 --> 00:01:00.270
So in the post, I wrote that if more social apps

00:01:00.270 --> 00:01:03.800
are built around infinite scrolling, Skylimit, as the

00:01:03.800 --> 00:01:05.720
name suggests, is built around finite scrolling.

00:01:05.720 --> 00:01:08.540
I wrote this on March 25th, and the newspaper article

00:01:08.570 --> 00:01:11.730
came on 26th, so I felt very good about that

00:01:11.730 --> 00:01:12.160
.

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:15.620
But finite scrolling can get you a long way.

00:01:15.620 --> 00:01:17.560
This is what the app looked like.

00:01:17.560 --> 00:01:21.400
It's basically a clone of Blue Sky, and the various

00:01:21.520 --> 00:01:23.860
things that look similar.

00:01:23.860 --> 00:01:26.620
But I'll show you the things that look different.

00:01:26.620 --> 00:01:29.620
The first thing you'll notice is that it says how many

00:01:29.760 --> 00:01:32.960
posts I received per day, and how many it shows.

00:01:32.960 --> 00:01:36.140
So I received about 1,300, it shows 600,

00:01:36.140 --> 00:01:37.380
and 19 edited.

00:01:37.380 --> 00:01:40.480
We'll come to the edited in a moment.

00:01:40.520 --> 00:01:41.380
So that's new.

00:01:41.380 --> 00:01:44.380
The other thing that's new is that it shows a number

00:01:44.520 --> 00:01:45.220
and a time.

00:01:45.260 --> 00:01:49.020
So every post is numbered starting from one, at midnight.

00:01:49.020 --> 00:01:50.700
So you know how much you're eating.

00:01:50.700 --> 00:01:51.900
It's like a calorie counter.

00:01:51.900 --> 00:01:53.300
My calorie count is 600.

00:01:53.300 --> 00:01:54.900
I know how much I'm eating.

00:01:54.900 --> 00:01:55.900
Okay?

00:01:55.900 --> 00:01:58.450
So every day I know how many posts I'm reading,

00:01:58.650 --> 00:02:01.300
how many I left, roughly, statistical.

00:02:01.300 --> 00:02:02.780
On weekends, it's actually less.

00:02:02.780 --> 00:02:04.100
On weekdays, it's more.

00:02:04.100 --> 00:02:06.460
It's a probabilistic curation.

00:02:06.460 --> 00:02:10.200
So I know exactly what I'm reading, and the other

00:02:10.200 --> 00:02:13.260
thing you can see is -- now I'm going to introduce

00:02:13.260 --> 00:02:13.760
myself.

00:02:13.760 --> 00:02:17.330
So if you go to my profile on Sky Limit,

00:02:17.330 --> 00:02:23.130
so I'm a climate scientist, and I have 600 followers

00:02:23.130 --> 00:02:23.360
.

00:02:23.480 --> 00:02:26.300
How do I limit the number of posts I see?

00:02:26.300 --> 00:02:30.560
If I'm going to see 600 posts a day, how

00:02:30.800 --> 00:02:33.040
do I limit that, okay?

00:02:33.040 --> 00:02:34.040
So this is also from the app.

00:02:34.040 --> 00:02:37.040
The app has a live graph, which shows for each follow

00:02:37.180 --> 00:02:39.310
ee, there are 600 of them.

00:02:39.360 --> 00:02:40.700
Only the active ones are shown.

00:02:40.700 --> 00:02:42.660
That's why it doesn't go up to 600.

00:02:42.660 --> 00:02:44.890
How many of their posts is a logarithmic scale,

00:02:44.890 --> 00:02:47.920
and this updates every two hours in your app.

00:02:47.980 --> 00:02:50.360
And I was very surprised when I saw this, because I

00:02:50.360 --> 00:02:51.820
had no idea what I was seeing.

00:02:51.960 --> 00:02:56.530
The yellow is how many people are posting, and the green

00:02:56.530 --> 00:02:58.850
is how much the app shows.

00:02:58.860 --> 00:03:00.920
And the red is a cap it posts.

00:03:00.920 --> 00:03:02.240
I call it the Sky Limit number.

00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:03.240
It's about 3.

00:03:03.240 --> 00:03:04.100
It's 2.

00:03:04.100 --> 00:03:04.640
7.

00:03:04.640 --> 00:03:08.210
It basically takes the area here and caps it and makes that

00:03:08.210 --> 00:03:09.570
600, okay?

00:03:09.620 --> 00:03:11.480
So if you're a quiet poster, and I'm a

00:03:11.480 --> 00:03:13.860
quiet poster, all your posts will be shown.

00:03:13.860 --> 00:03:16.740
So I wrote the app for quiet posters.

00:03:16.740 --> 00:03:19.240
But if you're a prolific poster, you'll only

00:03:19.500 --> 00:03:20.300
pick this many.

00:03:20.300 --> 00:03:22.700
And beyond that, it's probabilistic, right?

00:03:22.700 --> 00:03:25.840
And it automatically adjusts every two hours.

00:03:25.860 --> 00:03:27.520
Everything is done in the browser in IndexedDB.

00:03:27.520 --> 00:03:28.520
There's no server.

00:03:28.520 --> 00:03:30.740
This runs on GitHub pages.

00:03:30.740 --> 00:03:33.600
So 100 million people could use it tomorrow and still run if

00:03:33.610 --> 00:03:35.420
GitHub serves it or CloudFest serves it.

00:03:35.420 --> 00:03:37.640
So it's completely scalable.

00:03:37.640 --> 00:03:42.400
And so this number can vary depending on your situation.

00:03:42.400 --> 00:03:44.660
Let's see who those folks are.

00:03:44.660 --> 00:03:46.420
So this is the Sky Limit number.

00:03:46.420 --> 00:03:50.140
The other thing that it shows you in the same page as

00:03:50.140 --> 00:03:52.050
that, it has a sortable table.

00:03:52.140 --> 00:03:54.300
You can sort it by each column.

00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:58.110
How many posts my followers post, how many it allows,

00:03:58.110 --> 00:04:00.640
what the fraction that's shown.

00:04:00.640 --> 00:04:02.760
I initialized this in three days.

00:04:02.760 --> 00:04:06.500
So 80 protocol posting 54 posts per day.

00:04:06.500 --> 00:04:10.020
I'm seeing 6% out there because of the cap.

00:04:10.020 --> 00:04:12.610
So you can go down and you can check every two hours

00:04:12.860 --> 00:04:14.380
this gets updated in your app.

00:04:14.380 --> 00:04:17.640
So you get a complete view of who's posting what.

00:04:17.640 --> 00:04:20.340
And you can sort it by various columns, like it tracks

00:04:20.490 --> 00:04:21.160
engagement.

00:04:21.160 --> 00:04:23.520
You can see who's the most engaged with.

00:04:23.520 --> 00:04:24.520
All of that.

00:04:24.520 --> 00:04:27.980
And these are the amplification factors.

00:04:27.980 --> 00:04:30.820
So the normal, it gives you a three limit, but

00:04:30.830 --> 00:04:33.890
you can make it six or you can amplify it if you

00:04:33.890 --> 00:04:34.680
wish.

00:04:34.680 --> 00:04:36.600
And if you click on the number you saw, you can

00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:37.340
click on it.

00:04:37.340 --> 00:04:38.980
You can amplify the factors.

00:04:38.980 --> 00:04:42.520
So you have complete control over how many posts are shown.

00:04:42.520 --> 00:04:48.030
So that, back here, the other thing that you can

00:04:48.030 --> 00:04:51.500
see here, the sky limit number.

00:04:51.500 --> 00:04:54.150
I put it in my profile, and I'm hoping everybody

00:04:54.340 --> 00:04:55.780
puts it in their profile.

00:04:55.780 --> 00:04:58.560
And there's some really cool things that come out of this

00:04:58.630 --> 00:04:58.780
.

00:04:58.780 --> 00:04:59.780
Okay.

00:04:59.780 --> 00:05:02.780
So one of the advantages of being a last talk here is

00:05:02.920 --> 00:05:05.580
that you know what other people are talking about.

00:05:05.580 --> 00:05:09.420
And one of the things journalists pointed out that opaque AI algorithms

00:05:09.620 --> 00:05:12.560
, they don't know who they're going to reach.

00:05:12.560 --> 00:05:14.560
I don't post very much.

00:05:14.560 --> 00:05:17.040
Post something, I have no idea who will see it.

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:20.780
But if my followers are using sky limit, I can make

00:05:20.780 --> 00:05:22.440
these assertions.

00:05:22.440 --> 00:05:25.770
If your daily posting average is less than my 2.

00:05:25.770 --> 00:05:28.680
7 number, I will always see your post.

00:05:28.680 --> 00:05:30.960
That's guaranteed.

00:05:30.960 --> 00:05:32.400
And there's a priority mechanism.

00:05:32.400 --> 00:05:34.540
So it can divide posts into priority and regular.

00:05:34.540 --> 00:05:38.800
And by default, anything with the hashtag is considered priority.

00:05:38.800 --> 00:05:42.020
But the user can actually configure it.

00:05:42.020 --> 00:05:43.520
But it's not a convention in place.

00:05:43.520 --> 00:05:46.410
So right now, it just takes any hash post as priority

00:05:46.410 --> 00:05:46.660
.

00:05:46.680 --> 00:05:49.680
If your priority posting posts are less than average than my sky

00:05:49.820 --> 00:05:53.340
limit number, it will always be shown.

00:05:53.340 --> 00:05:55.520
And posts matching addition criteria are always shown.

00:05:55.520 --> 00:05:56.520
I'll talk about additions in a moment.

00:05:56.520 --> 00:05:58.420
But this gives guarantees.

00:05:58.420 --> 00:06:01.380
If my followers use sky limit, I can tell exactly how

00:06:01.380 --> 00:06:03.270
many people will see my post.

00:06:03.280 --> 00:06:04.620
And they see a limited number.

00:06:04.620 --> 00:06:06.180
And it will actually tell them if they haven't read my

00:06:06.180 --> 00:06:06.520
post.

00:06:06.520 --> 00:06:08.520
It counts the posts that haven't been read.

00:06:08.520 --> 00:06:10.800
It says you haven't read this many posts.

00:06:10.800 --> 00:06:12.320
And I'm okay with that number because it's a fixed

00:06:12.320 --> 00:06:13.020
number per day.

00:06:13.020 --> 00:06:16.860
If it's too much, I'll cut it down.

00:06:17.120 --> 00:06:20.800
So the infinite linear feed is just a UI construct.

00:06:20.800 --> 00:06:23.060
There's so much talk about custom feeds.

00:06:23.060 --> 00:06:24.840
But you can do more than custom feeds.

00:06:24.840 --> 00:06:26.620
You have to think outside the line of the feed, and

00:06:26.620 --> 00:06:31.040
I'll talk about additions, which is two-dimensional.

00:06:31.040 --> 00:06:33.520
So I love newspapers, as I said.

00:06:33.520 --> 00:06:37.940
So what you can do here is another tab called Periodic

00:06:38.090 --> 00:06:39.140
Editions.

00:06:39.140 --> 00:06:40.500
You can configure the additions.

00:06:40.500 --> 00:06:42.540
So you can have many additions a day.

00:06:42.540 --> 00:06:45.140
You can decide who your columnists are and what their sections

00:06:45.290 --> 00:06:45.500
are.

00:06:45.500 --> 00:06:48.000
It's basically a markdown file.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:51.100
You can see all their posts or posts which match their Subst

00:06:51.140 --> 00:06:51.790
ack URL.

00:06:51.800 --> 00:06:54.500
There are people I follow on Substack and they post about

00:06:54.610 --> 00:06:54.800
it.

00:06:54.860 --> 00:06:55.860
I want to see it.

00:06:55.860 --> 00:06:56.860
I don't want to miss it.

00:06:56.860 --> 00:07:00.320
It will automatically create that fixed times of the day.

00:07:00.320 --> 00:07:01.480
And this is what an addition looks like.

00:07:01.480 --> 00:07:03.480
So I like comics.

00:07:03.480 --> 00:07:05.720
So I follow XKCD, and it will only appear

00:07:05.720 --> 00:07:06.420
at noon.

00:07:06.420 --> 00:07:09.070
It could have been posted yesterday, but I'll see it

00:07:09.190 --> 00:07:09.680
at noon.

00:07:09.680 --> 00:07:11.600
And I don't need to see it immediately.

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:12.600
Okay.

00:07:12.600 --> 00:07:16.440
It doesn't clutter up my post.

00:07:16.540 --> 00:07:19.290
So you can collapse it so I have blue sky, and

00:07:19.390 --> 00:07:21.640
you can see blue sky as you want it.

00:07:21.640 --> 00:07:23.310
And the other thing it tells you here, I don't

00:07:23.310 --> 00:07:25.260
think you can see it, it says how many posts are

00:07:25.260 --> 00:07:26.180
unread.

00:07:26.180 --> 00:07:29.990
So you know if you read it, you don't have

00:07:29.990 --> 00:07:31.800
to go back to it.

00:07:31.800 --> 00:07:34.260
So just parting thoughts.

00:07:34.260 --> 00:07:35.520
Don't think of a linear feed.

00:07:35.520 --> 00:07:36.880
Think of multiple options.

00:07:36.880 --> 00:07:40.270
We had some talks earlier today at the Anisoda.

00:07:40.280 --> 00:07:42.940
You can have newspapers in blue sky.

00:07:42.940 --> 00:07:45.140
It's already working.

00:07:45.140 --> 00:07:46.400
And it's a very simple format.

00:07:46.400 --> 00:07:48.620
You can do that.

00:07:48.620 --> 00:07:51.600
And don't let your social media diet became an opaque AI

00:07:51.600 --> 00:07:52.460
construct.

00:07:52.460 --> 00:07:53.460
I like AI.

00:07:53.460 --> 00:07:54.460
I used AI to make this.

00:07:54.460 --> 00:07:57.020
But I like to verify the answers.

00:07:57.020 --> 00:07:59.690
So if you're using Addy to generate things, I

00:07:59.860 --> 00:08:01.600
would want to know what it is.

00:08:01.600 --> 00:08:04.600
I would want it to generate my digital layout, and look

00:08:04.740 --> 00:08:05.920
at it, then use it.

00:08:05.920 --> 00:08:08.580
So I think AI is helpful, but you want to check

00:08:08.720 --> 00:08:10.850
, and you want it to be transparent.

00:08:10.920 --> 00:08:14.210
But the nice thing about SkyLimit, it can

00:08:14.210 --> 00:08:18.670
limit your views, and transparently rely on human followers

00:08:18.670 --> 00:08:20.220
to do a curation for you.

00:08:20.220 --> 00:08:23.160
I follow people because I want to see their posts.

00:08:23.160 --> 00:08:25.720
And this ensures that if you don't post too much,

00:08:25.720 --> 00:08:27.660
I will definitely see your posts.

00:08:27.660 --> 00:08:31.500
And actually the one special hashtag which you'd recognize is called

00:08:31.620 --> 00:08:32.380
#weekly.

00:08:32.380 --> 00:08:35.380
Any post that has #weekly will always be shown,

00:08:35.520 --> 00:08:39.030
but it will only be done once a week because it tracks

00:08:39.030 --> 00:08:39.720
that.

00:08:39.720 --> 00:08:43.050
That way I can guarantee that if you post something, everybody

00:08:43.050 --> 00:08:45.560
who uses SkyLimit will see it.

00:08:45.680 --> 00:08:49.490
So if you're someone who posts a weekly column, you

00:08:49.490 --> 00:08:52.340
can guarantee that it will be seen.

00:08:52.340 --> 00:08:54.630
I did manage good times, so I'm going to show

00:08:54.630 --> 00:08:55.960
a few other features.

00:08:55.960 --> 00:08:59.260
Oh, you can't see it here.

00:08:59.260 --> 00:09:01.260
The colors are washed out.

00:09:01.260 --> 00:09:06.740
But when a post is read, the paper will actually age

00:09:06.740 --> 00:09:07.100
.

00:09:07.220 --> 00:09:09.180
I put it on my computer.

00:09:09.180 --> 00:09:11.180
So the paper looks old after 15 minutes.

00:09:11.180 --> 00:09:12.180
It tracks views.

00:09:12.180 --> 00:09:14.620
So if you're scrolling down and you want to have read

00:09:14.620 --> 00:09:16.780
the support, you'll see it immediately.

00:09:16.780 --> 00:09:23.080
And finally, why I'm writing this, because I don

00:09:23.080 --> 00:09:27.160
't know if you've seen Wall-E.

00:09:27.160 --> 00:09:29.240
This is what I'm afraid of, that you're sitting

00:09:29.240 --> 00:09:33.380
and watching your infinite doom scroll created by AI, and I

00:09:33.380 --> 00:09:35.480
don't want that feature.

00:09:35.480 --> 00:09:37.480
I want to control my views.

00:09:37.480 --> 00:09:38.480
So I'll leave you with those thoughts.

00:09:38.480 --> 00:09:40.440
We have 15 seconds.
